\section{Overview}
-Four different distributions: uniform, binomial, normal, and lognormal.
-Probability distributions form the basis for hypothesis testing and regression analysis.

\section{Probability Distribution}
-A probability distribution lists all possible outcomes of a random variable and the probability that each outcome will occur. 
-A discrete probability distribution is where a random variable can take on a countable number of outcomes. i.e. Quoted Stock prices when they are quoted in ticks.
-A continuous probability distribution is one where we cannot count the outcomes. i.e. Rates or return.

A probability function specifies the probability that a random variable takes on a specific value P(X = x) (written p(x)). For a continouous function the appropriate syntax is f(x). f(x) is called the probability density function.

Key properties of a probability function:
 1. p(x) lies between 0 and 1.
 2. The sunm of the probabilitiies of p(x) over all values of X is equal to 1.

Cumulative Distribution Function (CDF):
 P(X <= x) (often denoted F(x) for both continuous and discrete random variables).

